litMagPoems.title: this must be it
litMagPoems.content:
this must be it

the windows aren’t down
it’s December and it’s raining
but the radio’s up
my car is full
and I’ve felt this before
we’ve made a montage
in a coming of age
the sun is setting
orangely
on the coast of somewhere warm
though it’s December and it’s pouring:
this must be it
being deaf to directions
paying the music more mind
it doesn’t matter if we don’t get home
I’d drive to the end if it meant
keeping your company

e.m.

litMagPoems.title: daisies
litMagPoems.content:
daisies

i cleaned my room today
i dug deep
shifting through drawers
shoveling out dirt
thinking
wow, the weeds grew
i’d already uprooted the blatant greenery
polaroids on my mirror
pictures on my nightstand
sweatshirts far too large
but i missed the daisies
hidden under grass:
the first letters
reading, “i wouldn’t trade you for the world”
(remains true, you traded me for less)
back when a happy birthday
was worth your paper & penmanship

i collected the daisies
into a pretty box
& placed them out of reach

a younger version of myself
valued the daisy
a flower worthy of display
now i know
a daisy is a weed

e.m.
